CLUE: International sign of distress at sea
OUTPUT: ['Mayday - A standard international radio distress signal used when a vessel is in grave and imminent danger.', 'Pan-pan - An urgent situation call to communicate minor but still significant trouble without immediate threat of loss of life or the ship.', 'SOS - The Morse code distress signal, represented by three short signals followed by three long signals.', 'Alfa - A call for help in Greek shipping lanes; also used as a general maritime emergency signal.', 'NAVTEX - An automated system that relays navigational and safety information to ships at sea, including distress alerts.', 'Racon (Radar Beacon) - A transmitter installed on coastal structures that emits a unique radar return when activated during an emergency.', 'Flares - Visual signals used in maritime distress situations to attract attention from potential rescuers.', 'EPIRB (Emergency Position Indicating Radio Beacon) - A personal locator beacon that transmits a coded message on the 406 MHz distress frequency via satellite and earth stations.', 'SMCM (Safety Management Code Manual) - Guidelines for safe ship operations, including procedures for handling emergencies at sea.', 'Global Maritime Distress and Safety System (GMDSS) - An internationally agreed-upon set of safety procedures, types of equipment, and communication protocols used to increase safety and facilitate rescue operations in the maritime sector.', 'MMSI (Maritime Mobile Service Identity) - A unique nine-digit number assigned to a ship that can be used for identifying distress signals and locating vessels at sea.', 'SAR (Search And Rescue) - The organized efforts to locate, assist, and recover people in distress or imminent danger at sea.', 'GMDSS Alerting Authority - An organization responsible for issuing and coordinating distress alerts through the Global Maritime Distress and Safety System (GMDSS).', 'SATNAV (Satellite-based Navigation) - Advanced navigation systems that utilize satellite signals to provide accurate position, direction, and speed information critical in a maritime emergency.', 'EPIRB Plus - An advanced type of Emergency Position Indicating Radio Beacon with additional features such as GPS tracking and digital distress messages.', 'IALA Buoyage System (International Association of Marine Aids to Navigation and Lighthouse Authorities) - The system for marking buoys, beacons, and other navigation aids that help mariners determine their position and course at sea.', 'SARCAN (Search And Rescue Communication Assembly) - Devices installed on ships to facilitate communication in emergency situations and coordinate with Search and Rescue services.', 'Mayday Call - An internationally recognized verbal distress call used when a vessel is in grave danger, typically involving immediate threat of loss of life or the ship itself.', 'VHF Channel 16 (156.8 MHz) - The international maritime distress and safety frequency on which ships can broadcast distress calls and receive vital information for emergency response.', 'RTCR (Regularly Transmitted Call Signs) - Regularly used radio call signs that aid search and rescue coordinators in identifying vessels during non-emergency operations, but may also be employed in certain distress situations to avoid confusion with other signals.', 'SOLAS Convention (Safety of Life at Sea) - International maritime treaty that sets safety standards for ships, including requirements related to emergency preparedness and equipment like EPIRBs and racon beacons.', 'Inmarsat-C Marine Satellite Service - A satellite communication system used by ships for distress alerting, enabling them to transmit SOS signals when in remote areas or during emergencies at sea.']
